@* P2.1 — explains relationship types and the confidence model so a skeptical engineer understands why an edge exists. *@
<details class="mb-3">
    <summary class="text-muted small" style="cursor:pointer"><i class="bi bi-info-circle me-1"></i>How to read this graph — relationship types & confidence</summary>
    <div class="card card-body small mt-2">
        <div class="mb-2"><strong>Relationship types</strong></div>
        <div class="d-flex flex-wrap gap-3 mb-3">
            <span><span class="badge text-bg-success">Implements</span> a class realizes an interface</span>
            <span><span class="badge text-bg-primary">Inherits</span> a class extends a base class</span>
            <span><span class="badge text-bg-warning">DependsOn</span> constructor-injected / EXEC dependency</span>
            <span><span class="badge text-bg-secondary">References</span> uses a type / reads a table</span>
            <span><span class="badge text-bg-light border">PartOf</span> containment (member→type, column→table)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mb-1"><strong>Confidence — deterministic vs heuristic</strong></div>
        <div>
            <span class="badge text-bg-dark">1.00</span> <strong>deterministic</strong> — SQL foreign keys, containment, explicit base/interface lists.
            <span class="badge text-bg-dark">0.70–0.95</span> <strong>syntax-only C#</strong> name resolution — high when a type name is unique in the
            repository, lower (0.70) when disambiguated by namespace.
            <div class="text-muted mt-1">Edges are never invented: references to types/objects outside the repository are omitted, not guessed.</div>
        </div>
    </div>
</details>
